	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64211452"><p><div class="quote"><p>But sulfate particulates rain out on a time scale of about a year, while a well-designed orbit should last for hundreds of years.</p><p>And the side effects of sulfur oxides being put in the atmosphere (and coming OUT of the atmosphere) by the megatons are very unknown.</p></div><p>They rain out when released into the lower atmosphere. In the upper atmosphere/stratosphere, they can stay up for decades. This has been tracked when volcanoes launch this stuff that high. When it eventually makes it's way down, it raises the pH of rain slightly, depending on the concentrations. The effects of that are well known as it happens naturally with wildfires and volcanoes.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64211452">

